  • price: price in US dollars ($326–$18,823)

  • carat: weight of the diamond (0.2–5.01)

For illustration purpose, we extract a subset of 300 samples

Scenario 2. 10-fold Cross Validation (CV)

Suppose we would like to compare the following two models and select a better model with higher prediction accuracy:

  • Model 1: plain model (use carat as the only linear predictor)
  • Model 2: natural spline model (using ns(carat,3) as predictor)

Key steps:

  1. How to implement the above models in R?
  2. 10-fold CV procedure
  3. How to store predicted values from two different models?
# randomly split the observations into 10 categories
rows <- 1:nrow(subdiamond)

set.seed(123)
shuffled.rows <- sample(rows, replace = FALSE) ## shuffle the rows

B <- 10 # Number of folds

# divide the rows into 10 intervals and codes each row according to which interval they fall 
folds <- cut(rows, breaks = B, labels=FALSE) 

# create a dataset with predicted log price from cross validation
pred.data <- NULL

# do cross validation
for (i in 1:B){
    
    # divide data into test set (1/10) and training set (9/10)
    test.rows <- shuffled.rows[which(folds == i)]
    train.rows <-  shuffled.rows[which(folds != i)]
    
    test.data <- subdiamond[test.rows, ]
    train.data <- subdiamond[train.rows, ]
    
    # fit two models and obtain predicted value
    fit <- lm(logprice ~ carat, train.data)
    test.data$predicted.lm <- predict(fit, newdata = test.data[, "carat"])
    
    fitns <- lm(logprice ~ ns(carat, 3), train.data)
    test.data$predicted.ns <- predict(fitns, newdata = test.data[, "carat"])
    
    # stack and store new predicted data
    pred.data <- rbind(pred.data, test.data)
    
}


# Plot predicted log prices from CV
ggplot(pred.data) + 
  theme_bw() +
  geom_point(aes(carat, logprice), alpha = 0.2) +
  geom_point(aes(carat, predicted.lm, col = "c1")) +
  geom_point(aes(carat, predicted.ns, col = "c2")) + 
  scale_colour_manual(name = 'Model', values = c('c1' = 'blue','c2' = 'red'), 
                      labels = c('linear', 'natural spline')) +
  ggtitle("Predicted Log Prices from Cross Validated Models")

# cross-validated prediction error
mean((pred.data$logprice - pred.data$predicted.lm)^2)
## [1] 0.02698985
mean((pred.data$logprice - pred.data$predicted.ns)^2)
## [1] 0.01235098

Conclusion

In 10-fold cross validation, we observed that Model 2: natural spline with 3 degrees of freedom has lower Mean Squared Error and thus Model 2 performs better than Model 1 .
